s -- t15. Modernism, Antimodernism, and Hugh MacLennan’s Novels of the 1930s -- tWorks Cited -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn examination of the connections between modernist writers and editorial activities, Making Canada New draws links among new and old media, collaborative labour, emergent scholars and scholarships, and digital modernisms. In doing so, the collection reveals that renovating modernisms does not need to depend on the fabrication of completely new modes of scholarship. Rather, it is the repurposing of already existing practices and combining them with others – whether old or new, print or digital – that instigates a process of continuous renewal. Critical to this process of renewal is the intermingling of print and digital research methods and the coordination of more popular modes of literary scholarship with less frequented ones, such as bibliography, textual studies, and editing. Making Canada New tracks the editorial renovation of modernism as a digital phenomenon while speaking to the continued production of print editions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aMass mediazCanada. 0aModernism (Literature)zCanada. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Books & Reading.2bisacsh1 aAckerley, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBetts, Gregory, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClement, Tanya E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDalgleish, Melissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDisanto, Michael John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFast, Kristin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFortin, Marc André